 -- t13. Passing It On: Olive Schreiner and Bessie Head -- t14. Coetzee’s Schreiner, Schreiner’s Coetzee: Provincialising Allegory -- t15. Olive Schreiner In/Beyond the Museum -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamines Olive Schreiner’s writing, networks and legacies in new global, historical and contemporary contextsExamines aspects of Schreiner’s radical thought, including her feminism, anti-colonialism, anti-racism, pacifism, environmentalism, and ambivalent anarchism, as well as their impacts on civil rights movements, global feminisms, and global literary modernismsExplores revealing and sometimes unexpected connections, affinities and lines of influence that link Schreiner’s work with its widespread influence and afterlifeIncludes essays by leading and emerging Schreiner scholars working across English Studies, Modernist Studies, Comparative Literature, Sociology, Museum Studies, Publishing HistoryDiscusses Schreiner’s work in relation to major global literary and historical figures including W. E. B. DuBois, Martin Luther King Jr, Charles Freer Andrews, J. M. Coetzee, Virginia Woolf, Bessie Head and Patrick White, amongst othersChapters are driven by a shared impetus to uncover and analyse the anticipatory and galvanising roles of political and artistic forces that emerge from Southern Africa through case studies on SchreinerThis collection of essays considers the significance of South African-born writer, activist and thinker Olive Schreiner in international and multidisciplinary contexts in her time – and the ongoing relevance of her work to our own. A leading writer of New Woman Fiction at the fin de siècle, Schreiner influenced generations of readers, not to mention other writers. Taken together, these essays make the argument for a ‘new’ Schreiner Studies drawing on recent developments in scholarship on global and peripheral modernisms, activist networks and intersectionality, posthumanism, memory studies and intermediality. They position Schreiner’s work and legacy as significant for understanding literary and social archives, race and gender performance, and the rise of literary modernism in the global Anglosphere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Feminist.2bisacsh1 aBagchi, Barnita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarends, Heidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnes, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDriver, Dorothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFogg, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGill, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJose, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunslow Ong, Jade, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNivesjö, Sanja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOng, Jade Munslow, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRemmington, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSanders, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStanley, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSutcliffe, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTreagus, Mandy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVlies, Andrew van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalters, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWylie, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat